[1] Colombia (Valle del Cauca)
Date: Fri 12 Mar 2010
Source: Diario Occidente [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.diariooccidente.com.co/noticias_colombia71719.html>


Although up until now there have been 3200 confirmed dengue cases in
Valle del Cauca, the departmental [state or province equivalent]
secretary of health, Hector Fabio Useche, said that the situation is
complex but not critical. As of today [12 Mar 2010], the dengue
outbreak has left 9 dead in the department, 6 in Cali, 2 in Palmira,
and one in Jamundi.

"The outlook in Valle is worrying because people are dying of dengue;
it is a disease that exists, the mosquito is always going to exist,
[but] there shouldn't be mortality [because of it]," said the official.

The secretaries of health of Cali and Valle del Cauca are carrying
out various cultural prevention campaigns so that people detect
symptoms, avoid the presence of "white-footed" _Aedes aegypti_
mosquitoes, and receive timely treatment.

In Cali, the secretary of health has already carried out 4 shifts for
visiting various neighborhoods during the weekends in order to
orient, house-by-house, the Cali residents about how to confront
dengue. "Stating at 8:00 in the morning we go door-to-door in an
informative prevention campaign as part of a "crash" [action] that
has been developed for the whole municipality," said Marcelo
Castillo, environmental planning technician for Candelaria.

--
