[2] Ecuador (Galapagos)
Date: Thu 11 Mar 2010
Source: Vistazo, Ecuador [in Spanish, trans. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://www.vistazo.com/webpages/pais/?id=9194>


In total, there are 7 infected individuals with classical dengue
[virus] in the [Galapagos] archipelago: 6 in San Cristobal and one in
Santa Cruz, where an epidemiological barrier has been applied to
contain the disease.

The classical strain of the virus, transmitted by the mosquito _Aedes
aegypti_, appeared for the 1st time in the Galapagos in 2002. Then,
215 [dengue] cases were confirmed and the health authorities combated
dengue until the number of infections was reduced to 0 in 2004.

"People come form the mainland with the virus and only a few come to
be tested," explained Santiago Robles, coordinator of the Galapagos
Disease Service. This would constitute an obstacle for control of the
number of infected individuals.

Brigade members of the National Malaria Eradication Service (SNEM)
are fumigating areas where it is presumed that the vector mosquitoes
are found. In addition, they carry out control of new foci of
infection. However, the concern is the possibility that DHF will
appear, considering the limited [local] capacity to react [to that].
"An infected individual cannot stay in this unit. We have to move the
patient to a hospital with greater capacity on the continent," said
Ramiro Lopez, director of the Republic del Ecuador Hospital. He
indicated that the constant arrival of people and the intense rains
in recent weeks could have contributed to the reemergence of dengue.

--
Communicated by:
ProMED-ESP
<promed-esp@promedmail.org>

[One hopes that this small dengue outbreak will be quickly contained
and eliminated in this very popular tourist destination.

Maps showing the location of the Galapagos Islands in the Pacific
