[8] Paraguay (north)
Date: Mon 8 Mar 2010
Source: Reuters [in Spanish, trans. & summ. Mod.TY, edited]
<http://lta.reuters.com/article/topNews/idLTASIE6271BT20100308>


The Ministry of Public Health in Paraguay on Monday [8 Mar 2010]
raised an alert in the face of the 1st 2 dengue deaths since the
beginning of the [dengue] epidemic in September [2009] and warned
about a worsening situation due to the simultaneous circulation of 3
[of the 4] serotypes of the virus.

The director of Epidemiological Surveillance of the Ministry, Ivan
Allende, said that the administration of the office under his
direction registered some dengue 800 cases in the last half [of the
year 2009], an epidemic of low magnitude compared to previous years,
but more complicated due to the simultaneous circulation of the 3
[dengue virus] serotypes in the Concepcion and Amambay departments
[province or state equivalents] in the northern part of the country.
According to this official, this situation implies a greater risk for
possible appearance of serious cases "with hemorrhagic manifestations
in some cases or with visceral effects and multi-organ failure in others."

"While at the moment the [dengue virus] circulation is contained in
just 2 departments, given the mobility of the population we could
have it in all departments in a short period of time," he said.

Paraguay suffered its worst dengue epidemic in 2007, when 17 people
died and nearly 20 000 were infected.

The _Aedes aegypti_ mosquito, which transmits the disease [virus],
reproduces in catchments of clean water and in hot, humid climates in
Paraguay, which creates an environment propitious for its multiplication.

"We still have at least 2 months for the epidemic [to go], the months
of March and April, when serious [dengue] cases will continue to
appear," added Allende.

--
